04834nam a22006855i 9780748630790DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222009stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486307907 a10.1515/97807486307902doi  a(DE-B1597)616829  a(OCoLC)1302163503  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a941.1072221 aLenman, Bruce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnlightenment and Change :bScotland 1746-1832 /cBruce Lenman. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew History of Scotland : NHS00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Scotland on the Eve of the Agricultural and Industrial Revolutions -- t2. The Age of Islay 1746–1761 -- t3. Integration and Expansion 1760–1775 -- t4. Scotland and the American Revolution 1775–1784 -- t5. The First Phase of the Dundas Ascendancy 1784–1793 -- t6. The Melvilles and their System under the Pressures of War 1793–1815 -- t7. Change: The Underlying Time Bomb 1790–1815 -- t8. The Last Hurrahs of the Old Regime 1815–1827 -- t9. Meltdown and Reconfiguration 1827–1832 -- tConclusion: Enlightened Change? -- tSelected Further Reading -- tAppendix: Chronological Table -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe period from the Jacobite rebellion (1745) to the Scottish Reform Act (1832) saw the rise of some of the most influential thinkers of the contemporary world. Bruce Lenman provides a compact survey of developments in Enlightenment Scotland.The Reform Act spelled the end of political and social systems that had presided over industrial and agricultural revolutions turning Scotland from a rural society to one of the most urbanised and industrialised of European nations. Scotland also moved from being simply an active participant in the cultural life of western Europe to being a leader in a new, more expansive, Atlantic and European world where the ideas of its great Enlightenment thinkers circulated from Moscow to Philadelphia.The political framework for changes was the Union of 1707 which incorporated Scotland into the United Kingdom of Great Britain, and after 1800 Great Britain and Ireland. However, within the UK a distinctive political system run for most of this period by either the Dukes of Argyll or the so-called 'Dundas Despotism' dominated Scotland. This volume studies how that system first stimulated and exploited cultural and economic change and then was finally destroyed by it.This book is a revised and expanded edition of Integration and Enlightenment (Edinburgh University Press, 1993).Key Features:*discusses agricultural and industrial revolutions*considers Scottish urbanisation*examines the impact of mass migration and the Highland Clearances on Gaelic society*assesses the development of the Enlightenment thought through influential figures such as economist Adam Smith, philosopher David Hume, artist Henry Raeburn and architects the Adam brothers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnlightenmentzScotland. 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aLenman, Bruce P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074862514740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074863079040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748630790423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748630790/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aE